<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-40-0147 </DOCNO><TEXT>Characterizes the oligopolistic organizations involved in coal sale inPoland in the between-war period, especially the Robur, Progress andFulmen syndicates which covered 53% of the Polish market. The remaining43% was covered by independent sales offices and small coal enterprises.The reason why the whole market had not been taken over by syndicatesis explained by the cartelization of the coal industry and by state intervention.In the late 1930s trends toward strengthening the position of Polishstate capitalism in the coal industry became stronger and tendenciesto increase coal consumption in Poland appeared. 9 refs.</TEXT></DOC>